Congesti on at intersecti ons is measured using a concept called “level of service” (LOS).
LOS is an A to F grading system that describes the amount of congesti on present at an
intersecti on based on the average delays experienced by motorists. LOS A represents
minimal delay while LOS E and F represent gridlocked conditi ons. The most congested
movements at this intersecti on during the PM peak hour are the northbound left -
turn and the eastbound movements which both operate at level of service (LOS)
F. Southbound left -turns and westbound movements both operate at LOS D, while
southbound thru/right-turns and northbound thru/right-turns operate at LOS C and LOS
B respecti vely. Overall, the intersecti on operates at LOS E during the PM peak hour, with
an average delay per vehicle of 68 seconds.
Route 123 @ Route 1A (Highland Ave @ Newport Ave)-This intersecti on is also a four-
approach intersecti on with four separate signal phases. Northbound and southbound
left -turns are protected and proceed simultaneously followed by northbound and
southbound thru movements and right-turns. The westbound approach proceeds next
with a leading phase over the eastbound movements allowing for westbound left -turns
to be protected for a period of ti me. The eastbound and westbound approaches then
proceed simultaneously allowing for thru movements, left -turns and right-turns from
both directi ons. Figure 2 illustrates the signal phases at this intersecti on.

page.text: Recommendati ons to increase safety at these intersecti ons were made in
SRPEDD’s 1998 study and included protected left -turns from Route 123 onto
Routes 1 and 1A. Permitt ed/protected left -turns were introduced in 1997 in
the westbound directi ons on Route 123 at both intersecti ons. Despite these
improvements, these intersecti ons sti ll experience some safety issues. In order
to determine these safety issues, SRPEDD collected and reviewed motor vehicle
crash reports from the Att leboro Police Department. Two crash rates were
calculated for each intersecti on: the Accidents per Million Entering Vehicles
(ACC/MEV) crash rate and the Equivalent Property Damage Only (EPDO)
crash rate. The ACC/MEV rate indicates the overall exposure to crashes at an
intersecti on, while The EPDO rate measures the severity of crashes at a locati on,

page.text: MassDOT owns all three of these intersecti ons and therefore would be the
primary proponent of any improvements made to them. The recommended
improvements from this study could be categorized as short-term or long-term
and implemented as such. Short-term improvements would include the signal
ti ming changes at all three intersecti ons and the consolidati on of driveways
in and around the Route 1/Route 123 intersecti on. The major long-term
improvement would be a widening of Route 123 to include exclusive left -turn
lanes and signal phases at the eastbound and westbound approaches to the
The signal ti ming changes and driveway closures at the Route 1/Route 123
and Route 1A/Route 123 intersecti ons would be eligible for Highway Safety
Improvement Program (HSIP) funding from the Transportati on Improvement
Program (TIP) since they would help correct crashes at those locati ons. These
improvements could also be done without the use of TIP funds, however, if
MassDOT were to use their own maintenance funds. The opti mizati on of
signal ti mings at the Route 1/Route 123 intersecti on and the Route 1/Route
1A intersecti on could be done at minimal cost by MassDOT. The widening of
Route 123 would likely require land takings that would be the responsibility of
the city, however design and constructi on could be funded through HSIP or the
Congesti on Miti gati on Air Quality (CMAQ) program on the TIP. The city should
consult with MassDOT District 5 as well as MassDOT’s Oﬃ
Planning in Boston to move this project forward.
